      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to this lesson on using AI for creative assets safely. Over the last few years, AI tools have become remarkably capable at generating images, music, and even video, and that opens up some genuinely exciting possibilities for creators of all kinds. But alongside those possibilities come some real risks that are worth understanding before you dive in. Questions around copyright, ownership, and who actually has the rights to AI generated content are not always straightforward, and getting things wrong can have genuine consequences, whether that is a legal issue, a reputational problem, or simply wasting time and effort on something you cannot actually use. So in this lesson, we are going to walk through those risks in plain, practical terms, and by the end you will have a clear sense of how to approach AI creative tools in a way that is both confident and responsible. There is nothing here that should put you off using these tools. It is simply about using them wisely."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "So before we dive into the practical side of using AI for creative work, it is really important that we talk honestly about what can go wrong, because quite a lot can. First, AI tools are trained on vast amounts of existing content, which means the images, music, or video they produce can accidentally reproduce someone else's copyrighted work without you even realising it. On top of that, who actually owns the output is still a legal grey area in most countries, so you could find yourself in a tricky position. There are also serious concerns around deepfakes and synthetic media, where real people's likenesses can appear without their consent, which can cause genuine reputational damage. And because AI learns from human-generated data, it can inherit biases that lead to results that are skewed or even offensive. None of this means you should avoid AI entirely, but it does mean we need to use it thoughtfully, and that is exactly what this course is here to help you do."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So let's talk about what can actually go wrong when you use AI to generate images. There are a few things worth being aware of. First, AI tools are trained on huge amounts of existing content, which means the images they produce can sometimes look a little too similar to real people or existing artwork, and that can cause problems. There's also a lot of legal uncertainty around who actually owns an AI-generated image, and that varies depending on where you are in the world. On top of that, if the data used to train the tool was biased in some way, that bias can show up in the visuals it creates. You might also notice that AI-generated images sometimes get small details wrong, like hands with too many fingers or garbled text. And finally, if you use these images in commercial work without checking the licensing terms, your organisation could face real legal exposure. So it's definitely worth pausing before you publish."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "So now that we know AI can generate creative assets quickly, let's talk about what can go wrong, because there are some genuine risks you need to be aware of. First, AI tools are trained on existing work, so the style or even the content they produce can be a little too close to someone else's copyrighted material, and that can land you in trouble. You might also find that generated images contain faces that look like real, identifiable people, or logos that belong to actual brands, neither of which you have permission to use. Beyond the legal side, there are other concerns too. AI can produce visuals or text that look convincing but are factually wrong or misleading, which matters a great deal if you are publishing content professionally. And finally, because of the data these tools are trained on, the images they generate can reflect hidden biases, for example, consistently showing certain roles as belonging to one gender or ethnicity. These are all things worth keeping a close eye on."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "Now, one of the trickiest areas with AI-generated content is understanding who actually owns what you've created, and whether you're safe to publish it. The honest answer is: it depends entirely on the tool you're using. Many AI models are trained on vast amounts of existing content, which means the outputs could potentially include elements derived from copyrighted material. Before you publish anything commercially, always read the platform's terms and conditions, because some tools actually retain a licence over the content you generate. If you're working on client projects or anything commercially sensitive, that ambiguity becomes a real problem. It's also worth checking whether your tool offers any indemnification cover, meaning they'll back you up if a copyright claim arises. Some do, many don't. So as a general rule of thumb, if you're not completely certain about the ownership status of an AI output, treat it as unlicensed until you've confirmed otherwise. It's a simple habit that can save you a great deal of trouble."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "Now, even with the best tools at your disposal, there are some common mistakes that catch people out, so let us walk through how to avoid them. First, always look critically at what the AI produces. These systems can reflect biases that exist in their training data, so do not just accept the output at face value. Similarly, be careful about asking AI to mimic the style of a specific living artist or creator, as this can stray into murky copyright territory. When you do use AI-generated content, be transparent about it and credit it appropriately. Your audience and colleagues will appreciate the honesty. Before anything goes live, make sure a real human being has reviewed it properly. That might sound obvious, but it is surprisingly easy to skip that step when you are working quickly. The golden rule here is that AI is a tool to support your judgement, not replace it. Keep yourself in the loop at every stage."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "Before you hit publish on anything you've created with AI, run through this quick checklist. First, make sure there are no copyright conflicts lurking in your output, especially with images or audio that might echo existing protected work. Next, check that no real, identifiable faces have appeared in your visuals, because that can cause serious legal and ethical headaches. If you've generated any music or lyrics, listen and read carefully for anything that sounds too close to a known song. It's more common than you'd think. You'll also want to confirm what your specific platform actually allows when it comes to AI-generated content, because the rules vary quite a bit and they're changing all the time. And finally, get into the habit of saving your generation prompts. If a question ever arises about how something was created, having that record is genuinely useful. It only takes a couple of minutes, and it could save you a lot of trouble later on."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So before we wrap up this lesson, let's pull everything together into a few principles worth keeping in mind. First, always check the rights situation before you use anything AI has generated, whether that's an image, a piece of music, or a video clip. If your organisation or client needs you to disclose that AI was involved, make sure you do that, and keep a record of what tools you used and when. Be careful about what you put into these tools as well. Avoid uploading real people's faces, voices, or any private data. And once you have your output, don't just publish it straight away. Take a moment to review it for bias, accuracy, and whether it actually fits your brand. Finally, if all of this feels a little overwhelming, that's completely normal. Start small. Pick one tool, try it on one project, and build your confidence gradually from there. You don't need to do everything at once."
        }
      ]
    }
